======================================================================
  SECTION 2: Neron-Severi Group -- Theoretical Setup
======================================================================

--- 2a. Definition and rank for abelian varieties ---
  For an abelian variety A of dimension g over Q:
    NS(A) = Pic(A) / Pic^0(A)
    rank(NS(A)) = rho(A)  (Picard number)
    NS(A) embeds into H^2(A, Z)

  For J_0(143):
    dim J_0(143) = g = 13  (M8-certified)
    H^2(J_0(143)) has rank 2g*(2g-1)/2 = 2*13*(25)/2 = 325
    NS(J_0(143)) rank rho >= 1 (theta divisor is algebraic)
    NS(J_0(143)) rank rho <= 2*g^2 + 1 = 339 (Lefschetz bound)

    g                    = 13
    H^2 rank (2g choose 2) = 325
    rho_min (theta)      = 1
    rho_max (Lefschetz)  = 339

--- 2b. Hecke action on NS ---
  The Hecke algebra T = Z[T_p : p prime, p not| 143] acts on J_0(143).
  Each Hecke eigenform f of level 143 contributes a factor A_f to J_0(143).
  Level 143 = 11 * 13: 13 newforms (matching genus g=13).

  Hecke endomorphisms generate End^0(J_0(143)) over Q.
  NS(J_0(143)) tensor Q contains the Neron-Severi part of End^0(A).

  Since J_0(143) is simple over Q (no CM factors at level 143),
  End^0(J_0(143)) tensor Q is a number field or division algebra.
  This constrains rho significantly.

--- 2c. 120-cell geometry -- NS rank constraint from Z Tower ---
  Z = 15  (certified: Z = rank(M_ij) = 15, from M8G_Correction)
  120-cell: 120 vertices, 120 cells
  Z_effective for NS bound: Z = 15

  NS rank bound from 120-cell geometry:
    rho(J_0(143)) <= g + Z = 13 + 15 = 28
    This gives rho <= 28, tighter than Lefschetz bound 339
  rho_120cell_bound = 28

